# string_concat_move_test.deor
# Confirms `move` is inert inside a `+` string-concat chain — concatenation
# compiles to `[...].concat()`, which only ever borrows its operands
# (`.as_str()`), so there's nothing for `move` to opt out of. This is the same
# kind of inertness `move` already has on a Copy-type primitive (see move.md):
# writing it isn't wrong, it just doesn't change anything. `nates_string`
# stays valid after the chain either way.

fn void main()
	string nates_string = "hello"
	print(move nates_string + " hi")
	print(nates_string)

# expect:
# hello hi
# hello
